ttps://online.ucf.edu/teach-online/develop/accessibility-of-online-courses-section-508/creating-accessible-course-content/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creating Accessible Course Content</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website. Online @ UCF. University of Central Florida.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Additional Information</h3>\n<ul>\n <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Download the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/resources/quickref/quickref.pdf\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Quick Reference: Web Accessibility Principles PDF</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from the WebAIM website.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Download the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/standards/wcag/WCAG2Checklist.pdf\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.0 Checklist PDF</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from the WebAIM website.</span>','Tips for Implementing Universal Design for Learning in Teaching Materials','','inherit','closed','closed','','216-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-27 20:20:23','2015-09-27 20:20:23','',216,'www.celt-staging.com2015/09/27/216-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(219,1,'2015-09-27 19:51:31','2015-09-27 19:51:31','<b>Related CELT resources</b>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.celt.iastate.edu/teaching-resources/course-planning/udl/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Universal Design for Learning Overview</span></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.celt.iastate.edu/teaching-resources/course-planning/udl-course-design/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tips for Implementing Universal Design for Learning in Course Design</span></a>\r\n<h2>Quick and easy to implement</h2>\r\n<h3>Accessibility Statement</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">All course syllabi should include the syllabus statement on accommodating disabilities. All students become aware of Student Disability Resources and the process for requesting accommodations.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">: For the appropriate wording visit the </span><a href=\"http://www.celt.iastate.edu/teaching-resources/course-planning/syllabi/recommendations-syllabus/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">CELT Faculty Senate Recommendations for Syllabus Inclusion</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website.</span>\r\n<h3>Color Coding and Color Contrast</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Color is a key visual signaling device for humans. Ensure good color contrast for text/graphics/charts and backgrounds. Content should be legible in black and white. This fix improves legibility for all students.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Supplement color-coding with text/icon coding. Do not use color alone to convey meaning; e.g., use and asterisk (*) or other symbol; and if color is used, use it very sparingly. If you are unsure about the accessibility of the colors you are applying to documents that you plan to put online in any format, please visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Color Contrast Checker provided by WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website.</span>\r\n<h3>Fonts</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Use </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/fonts/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">sans-serif fonts</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (basic, simple, easily-readable) designed for legibility on the computer screen (e.g., Arial, Verdana, Helvetica). This fix improves legibility for all students.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Font Readabilty at the WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn about accessible fonts.</span>\r\n<h3>Image ALT Text</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Use ALT text for all content images to convey the meaning of the image within the context of the course material. This allows any student unable to view the image to understand its content.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/alttext/#basics\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Alternative Text Basics at the WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn how to incorporate ALT text in your course.</span>\r\n<h3>Link Text</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Links are a basic functionality of web content; therefore, inaccessible links are one of the most severe barriers to overall accessibility.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Linked text is descriptive instead of just “click here.”</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Best example: </span></i>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Please visit the </span><a href=\"http://www.iastate.edu\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Iowa State University</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> web page.</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Fair example: </span></i>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here is the </span><a href=\"http://www.iastate.edu\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Iowa State University</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> web page.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The screen reader software knows there is an upcoming link in the document and is set up to search for text by the link description. The words, “Click here” would not provide enough information to the user about the website.</span>\r\n\r\n<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Worst example: </span></i>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Click </span><a href=\"http://www.iastate.edu\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">here</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to view the Iowa State University web page.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Lastly, verify that all links work.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Improved link text is often more visible and increases student confidence in finding content. Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/hypertext/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Links and Hypertext WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website</span>\r\n<h3>MS Word Files</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Microsoft Word (MS Word the .doc and to a lesser extent, .docx) is currently the most common word processor on the market. Improved functionality increases student confidence in finding and interpreting content.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">: Export or save the MS Word document as a PDF. Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/word/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Microsoft Word WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn how to make MS Word accessible.</span>\r\n<h3>PDF Files</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PDF files may be the only way to present some types of information and need to be made accessible or content must be provided in alternative format. Improved functionality increases student confidence in finding and interpreting content.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">: Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/acrobat/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PDF Accessibility WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn how to convert to PDF.</span>\r\n<h3>PowerPoint</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Microsoft PowerPoint is a popular tool for creating presentations. Accessible PowerPoint documents will help to ensure that students engage more with the presentation and gain the most information.Visit </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/powerpoint/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">PowerPoint Accessibility WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn how to create accessible PowerPoint presentations.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Export or save the PowerPoint as a PDF. Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/word/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Microsoft Word WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn how to make an accessible MS Word document.</span>\r\n<h2>Longer term goals</h2>\r\n<h3>Audio/Video</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Provide transcripts for audio clips and synchronous captioning for video clips. Captions also benefit non-native speakers or students experiencing audio glitches.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">: Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/captions/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Captioning, Transcripts and Audio Descriptions WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website.</span>\r\n<h3>Audio/Video from Outside</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Transcripts or captioned videos must be provided to students requiring an accommodation. However, the distribution of the content may be restricted because of copyright. Captions also benefit non-native speakers or students experiencing audio glitches.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Find captions/transcripts if you can.</span>\r\n<h3>External Documents</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The content of any non-Iowa State University resource such as a Web site, PDF article from a journal, slides from external sources or other non-Iowa State University informational resource must be provided in an accessible format to students requiring an accommodation. In some cases, it is permissible to copy and reformat content just for students with a documented need.</span>\r\n<h3>Image Long Description</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For complex images, consider including a description in the ALT text or a link to the description to the text in another location. Then, all students could have different options to process the image.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/alttext/#complex\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Complex Image at the WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn about long descriptions.</span>\r\n<h3>Math Equations</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">MathML, a low level specification for scientific content on the web and beyond, will facilitate conversion of equations.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How: </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Equations could be created with a technology such as WIRIS, an equation editor that is active in Blackboard, allows rapid conversion.  Visit </span><a href=\"https://en-us.help.blackboard.com/Learn/9.1_Older_Versions/9.1_SP_14/Instructor/040_In_Your_Course/020_Content_Editor#using_math_editor\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Using the Math Editor </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">on the Blackboard help website to learn how to use the tool.</span>\r\n<h3>Multimedia</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Using images, sound and animations can often be more comprehensible than large blocks of text. Some people even recommend icons for users with cognitive impairments. Screen readers cannot interpret multimedia elements without textual assistance.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Always implement ALT text, extended text descriptions and/or captioning or transcripts</span>\r\n<h3>Table Captions and Column Headings</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do not use tables for layout and design purposes. Restrict tables to presentation of data. Accessible table design includes additional information for all students to use.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Consider alternatives to tables such as lists for complex tables. Visit </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/tables/data\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creating Accessible Tables on the WebAIM</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website to learn how to create simple tables, captioning, and identify table rows, columns and headers.</span>\r\n<h3>Unicode for Foreign Languages</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Unicode makes data exchange between operating systems and foreign languages easier.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How:</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Consider how screen readers can access foreign language content. Visit the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/techniques/screenreader/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Designing for Screen Reader Compatibility</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on the WebAIM.</span>\r\n<h3>Adapted from the following resources</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Accessibility and Usability at Penn State University. </span><a href=\"http://accessibility.psu.edu/courses/courseguidelines/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Course Accessibility Guidelines</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Retrieved from </span><a href=\"http://accessibility.psu.edu/courses/courseguidelines/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">http://accessibility.psu.edu/courses/courseguidelines/</span></a></li>\r\n <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Accessibility and Usability at Penn State University. </span><a href=\"http://accessibility.psu.edu/accommodations/usability/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Accessibility vs. Usability vs. W3C Web “Standards”</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Retrieved from http://accessibility.psu.edu/accommodations/usability/</span></li>\r\n <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://online.ucf.edu/teach-online/develop/accessibility-of-online-courses-section-508/creating-accessible-course-content/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Creating Accessible Course Content</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> website. Online @ UCF. University of Central Florida.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Additional Information</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Download the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/resources/quickref/quickref.pdf\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Quick Reference: Web Accessibility Principles PDF</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from the WebAIM website.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Download the </span><a href=\"http://webaim.org/standards/wcag/WCAG2Checklist.pdf\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines 2.0 Checklist PDF</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from the WebAIM website.</span>','Tips for Implementing Universal Design for Learning in Teaching Materials','','inherit','closed','closed','','216-revision-v1','','','2015-09-27 19:51:31','2015-09-27 19:51:31','',216,'www.celt-staging.com2015/09/27/216-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(220,1,'2015-09-27 20:21:06','2015-09-27 20:21:06','<b>Related CELT resources</b>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.celt.iastate.edu/teaching-resources/course-planning/udl/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Universal Design for Learning Overview</span></a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.celt.iastate.edu/teaching-resources/course-planning/udl-course-design/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Tips for Implementing Universal Design for Learning in Course Design</span></a>\r\n<h2>Quick and easy to implement</h2>\r\n<h3>Accessibility Statement</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">All course syllabi should include the syllabus statement on accommodating disabilities. All students become aware of Student Disability Resources and the process for requesting accommodations.</span>\r\n\r\n<b>How</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">: For the appropriate wording visit the </span><a href=\"http://www.celt.iastate.edu/teaching-resources/course-planning/syllabi/recommendations-syllabus/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">CELT Faculty Senate Recommendations for Syllabus 